people.name: Borje  Hansson(Hagborg)
people.notes: Have picture at age 25 (1893) 3 years after emigrating to Canada from Skane(Scania) Sweden. After working a year in Canada, he sent tickets to his sister Martha and brother Andrew to come to Canada. His polio-crippled brother Ola remained and taught school for many years in Sweden. Two sisters Elsa and Una also remained in Sweden. All had families. - WAFH Note - also sister Matta, Elna remained in Sweden. Worked loading ties on Montreal docks first. Then came to Manitoba as farm labourer. Anvil at Treherne displayed which he could pick up with little finger. Began hauling wood & water in Winnipeg in 1890's on cart. Turned into Hagborg Fuel Co. which was major coal dealer. Buried in lot 1895 Brookside Cemetery Winnipeg, Manitoba, Canada. Married Karolina Nelson 09/14/1892 Changed name from Hansson to Hagborg (after Hagestaborg ) ca 1883 as Swedish military encouraged name changes (ie was confusing in more modern world to have your last name your father's first name followed by either son or dotter - or maybe even after your mother's first name) Buried in Plot 1859 Brookside Cemetery 3001 Notre Dame Winnipeg MB Canada

people.name: Clarence  Hagborg
people.notes: After coming to Meadows with his parents, stayed at Clandeboye with his aunt and attended school there until the school at Meadows was built. He worked at home until 1916 when he went to St. Paul Minnesota to work for the winter as a barn boss for Jim Hill, a railway magnate. In 1918 he was conscripted to the Canadian Army, returning in 1919. He purchased 240 acres from W. L. Parrish and continued to live at home and farm with the family until his marriage in 1937. They bought a farm at Argyle, Manitoba where they lived until 1968. Clarence also continued to farm his land at Meadows until he sold it to Boonstras.

people.name: Harry  Hagborg
people.notes: Recalls that in 1912 summer family bought 25 HP International tractor that pulled 5 breaker ploughs. Harry and brothers broke 100 acres on section 31-12-1W. In 1922 after helping to complete an early harvest at home, Harry went with Tom Sinclair to Flaxcombe SK as a harvester. He spent a winter at a Kenora paper mill as mill wright helper. Also worked 1 winter for Fort Rouge Coal Co. Married in 1934. Then purchased farm from the Soldier Settlement Board which had been occupied by John Smith family. This was in addition to 240 acres bought previously from W. Herriot. Harry has been noted for his mechanical inventiveness & holds a patent for  a swath mover. Sold the farm in 1967 to son Walter. Spoke only Swedish til age 6. Has amusing story about causing teacher to faint when he was 7 and responsible for starting the morning fire in school - cut himself & could see tendons, knuckles - Brandy was impressed! Also at same age had to go 7 miles to Marquette for groceries by himself. Ended up sleeping in a haystack overnight.

people.name: Victor  Hagborg
people.notes: Oldest of family, has clear recollection of moving to Meadows and seeing nothing but a big swamp - no roads, just a railway. He worked at home on the farm and at various other interesting jobs during the winters - hauling fill for the basement of the Fort Garry Hotel; helping to dig the reservoir on Logan and McPhillips; and at Arctic Ice for 3 winters. In 1914, Victor and his friend Andy Hanson, went to Pine River in northern Manitoba where they tended a trap line for the winter. The next 2 winters he spent at Berens River and near Hodgson, trapping and hunting. In 1918 he was concripted into the Canadian Army, Fort Garry Horse Division. After a short period of training he was sent to England to await draft for France. The Armistice was signed. He stayed in Meadows til 1922 when went to Bresaylor, SK to manage a farm for W. Herriot. Married Bessie & returned to Meadows in 1924 & built own home on farm. Victor has always been interested in making Meadows a better community & has held many municipal executive positions. Had large rock collection & did cutting/

people.name: Anders(Andrew)  Hagborg(Hansson)
people.notes: When Andrew was 20 he was brought to Winnipeg by his eldest brother Borje. Andrew worked for Borje delivering water, selling it by the pail to city hotels and restaurants, hauling it from artesian wells northwest of the city. In 1895 he married Johanna Wall who came to Winnipeg when she was 16 and worked at Jerry Robinson's home. After their marriage Andrew worked at Arctic Ice Co. and Johanna kept a boarding house. In 1899 they bought a farm and moved to Starbuck. Andrew continued to work at Arctic Ice in the winter. In 1903 they bought 240 acres at Meadows from Mr. Osterberg. They moved to Meadows in 1903 via horse and buggy. Andrew died of pneumonia in 1905 while Johanna was pregnant with Andy. Johanna married employee Victor Carlson in 1907. Emigrerade fran foraldrahemmet pa Hagestad 43 till Kanada ihop med syskonen Borje och Matta.

people.name: Per  Trulsen (Trulsson)
people.notes: Trulsen (Trulsson), Per. Rusthllare, bo  .Vemmenhg 22. Fdd mjligen p 1620-talet(???). Dd 1712  .Vemmenhg 22. Per Trulsson vertog frldragrden, nummer 22 i .Vemmenhg, efter fadern. I 1696 rs jordebok terfinnes fljande mycket korta notering fr 22:an: Trulls Larsson, nu Per Trullsson . Ungefr vid denna tid tycks sledes garskiftet ha gt rum. Denne P.T. och hela hans slkt finns i mlande ordalag beskriven i ttlingen Johannes Hellners memoarer. J.Hellner var fdd 1866 och blev med tiden bl.a. statsrd men innehade en mngd poster som frtroendevald. Han var bl.a. dir. i Svenska trvaruexportfreningen, i Svenska vattenkraftsfreningen, i Tobaksmonopolet mm. (se kopia under Per Trulsson i slktprm). I sina memoarer skriver allts denne Hellner under kapitlet Slkten och hemmet 1866-1879 om sina frfder och nmner d Per Trulsson och massor av hans ttlingar: Slktgrden i stra Vemmenhg var hemmanet nr. 22, ett halvt mantal. Vid tiden fr Roskildefreden 1658 var detta ett s kallat kanikhemman, det vill sga anslaget till domkyrkan i Lund. r 1680 reducerades hemmanet frn den store jorduppkparen greve Gus staf otto Stenbock och fick karaktr av rusthllshemman. Genom ett av kammarkollegiet utfrdat brev av 18 december 1761 frvandlades jorden till skattehemman, det vill sga med gandertt fr bon. Av byggnaderna p hemmanet nr. 22 som tminstone under 1800-talet kallades Toftebo, finnes ingenting kvar. P hemmanets jord ligger numera sex grdar och ett lderdomshem. ldste knde medlem av slkten p fdernet r Truls Larsson, vilken r 1661 var bosatt p kanikhemmanet i stra Vemmenhg. En son, Lars Trulsson, frekommer i jordebckerna frn 1671 och vertager hemmanet efter faderns dd, vilken intrffade omkring 1685. Lars Trulsson avled snart och eftertrddes p hemmanet av brodern, Per Trulsson, vilken tidigare, i mantalslngderna p 1680-talet, redovisats som boende p en gatutomt, det vill sga ett omrde som icke satts i mantal. Nr jag var pojke brukade min farfar om jularna komma och hlsa p mina frldrar i Svedala. Under kvllarna voro farfar och jag ofta hnvisade till varandras sllskap och roade oss med att dra tavl . Det var ett spel, som var ltt att ordna med sm resurser. Under spelet brukade farfar bertta fr mig vad han hrt av sin far om vr skt, ngot som jag var mycket intresserad av. S lngt farfars kunskap ndde tillbaka, hade frfderna varit hemmansgare i Vemmenhgs hrad. Farfars far hette Jacob Hansson, dennes far Hans Trulsson och dennes farfar Per Trulsson. Mellan de bgge senare mste allts hava funnits en Truls Persson, men om denne visste farfar ingenting. Att han knde Per Trulssons namn berodde p en slkttradition om en bragd, som Per Trulsson utfrt under snapphanekriget. Ett parti snapphanar hade huserat i stra Vemmenhg, dr Per Trulsson hade sitt hemman, och Per Trulsson hade med en plyxa slagit ihjl tolv snapphanar. Han hade sedan lagt liken p en vagn och krt dem till Lilla Bedinge och snkt dem i sjn. Plyxan hade bevarats i slkten i flera generationer och farfar hade i sin barndom sett den i sin fars grd, men sedan hade den p obekant stt kommit bort. Per Trulsson skulle ha varit en jttestark man och styrkan hade gtt i arv till hans avkomlingar. Per Trulsson skulle allts ha varit i sin mannalder p 1670-talet. Dennes sonsons sonson Hans Jacobsson, min farfar, var fdd ngot av de sista ren p 1700-talet, om jag minns rtt var det 1798. Slkthemmanet i stra Vemmenhg var frmodligen ett bra hemman. Min farfar var ende sonen till Jacob Hansson och rvde allts grden. Han gifte sig med Elna Srensdotter, som var en frmgen bonddotter av en vitt utgrenad slkt, i vilken namnet Sren var vanligt. Farfar hade allts vl frspnt, men nd gick det utfr fr honom. Han hade ssom enda sonen ej blivit hllen till arbete i sin ungdom och ven sedan han blivit gift, ville han ej arbeta p sin grd, utan hll mest till p krogen. Drtill var hans hustru sjuklig. Fljden var att han efter en del r fick g ifrn fdernegrden. Han kpte d istllet en mindre grd i Lilla Bedinge, men som han fortfarande vansktte sitt arbete, slutade det med att han fick g ifrn ven denna grd. Sedan fick han frsrja sig med att taga tjnst hos andra. Bouppteckning efter Per Trulsson frrttades den 14/2 1713 (nr. 20). Hemmet verkar ha varit mrkligt mediokert, utan minsta tecken p lyx eller flrd. Bland lsret nmns: 1 kopparkiettel, 1 mssingskiettel, 1 jrnkakellugn, 1 sgh, 1 nafwer, 1 wedxe, 1 bred wedxe. TRWAHROR: 1 ekekiste, 1 stndtunna, 1 wrskp, 1 bakstohll, 1 baketrugh, 1 kierne, 1 spand, 1 bryggekarr, 1 handqwarn, 1 furusng, 2 spinnercke 1 wagn med dess behr, 3 slr. OXER OCH KOOR: 1 gammal brunstiernat oxe, 1 swart gielen koo. HSTER OCH STOO: 1 swartblset hst 8 hr gammal, 1 rdblset, 1 rdblset flija 4 hr och 1 swartstirnet fll Enligt Helmer Frennings register ver Vemmenhgs hrads dombcker frekommer Per Trulsson den 30/10 1727 samt 5/2 1730, detta oaktat att han d var dd sedan mnga r. Mlet 1727 handlar om en skuld som Per Trulsson i livstiden haft till handelsmannen Testrup i Ystad. Dennes sterbhus hade nu instmt Per Trulssons son Truls angende denna skuld, p 30 daler silvermynt. Truls framhll att hans fader afgdt uti fattigdom och at inga penningar woro at tillg . Faderns bouppteckning uppvisades som ett bevis p denna fattigdom och sonen Truls framhll ven att boet varit s fattigt att han sjlv inte ftt rva ngot!! people.notes: In 1926 he ventured to Winnipeg to work for his uncle's company, Hagborg Fuel Company.he worked there for 3 winters and for the Fort Rouge Coal Company for 4 winters. Summer always found Andy back home, helping on the farm. In 1935 he married Henny Enquist from Chatfield. They moved into their new house across the road from the "home place" and started to build up their own farm. In 1936 the first trees were planted in what was to become a prize-winning yard. In addition to helping in Meadows organisations, Andy and Henny have taken an active part in the Rosser Curling Club. Winter finds them on the "Bonspiel Trail". In 1970 Andy was the Ward 1 councillor for Rosser Municipality Through the years Andy bought more land. They have 2 children, Shirley and Violet.

people.name: Johanna  Wall
people.notes: Johanna was the fourth of seven sisters. Her sisters were: Karna - crippled at age of 18. She spent most of her life in the hospital. She lived to be quite old. Maria - Married Peter Nordin. They came to Canada and settled at Teulon. They had 8 children: Vera, Edwin, Clarence, Henry, Helmer, Margot, Victor and Arthur. Anna - married ? Sveinson. They had four children: Ingeborg, Eva, Gulli and Tore. Matilda - came to Canada married to ? Johnson. They had three children: Arthur, Signe, & Anna. Augusta - came to Canada and died very young. Kjestin - married to ? Goranson, had two sons Nils and Harold. Johanna came to Canada at age 16. Visited Sweden with Carlson daughters Doris and Edith in 1919.
